{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_juniper_ver01/data/sn85053305/00340581932/1923110201/0357.xml":{"full_text":"PRINCIPLE OF FREE SPEECH IN\nTWO CITIES AFTER HARD FIGHT\nAUTHORITIES IN NEW KENSINGTON, PA., AND\nBROCKTON, MASS. YIELD TO PUBLIC OPINION\nIN FREE SPEECH TESTS.\nTwo important victories in the na\ntionwide fight for freedom of speech\u2014\nat Brockton, Mass, and New Kensing\nton, Pa.\u2014are reported by the Amer\nican Civil Liberties Union. In both\ntowns the efforts of local officials to\nsuppress lawful gatherings of their\ncitizens have been nullified through\nthe pressure of public opinion and the\nintercession of the civil liberties body.\nRetreating from his arbitrary posi\ntion of the last few months, D. Burns\nBurgess of New Kensington his issued\na permit for a meeting of Italian\nworkers at Garibaldi Hall, on October\n21, with Carlo Tresca the editor of\nthe Italian monthly \"II Martello,\" as\nprincipal speaker. It will be the first\nsuch gathering to take place there in\nmany months without police interfer\nence.\nThe refusal of Mr. Burns to grant\npermit for a similar meeting on\nSeptember 30 makes the turn of af\nfairs the more significant. A repre\nsentative of the Civil Liberties Union\nwas to have spoken on the same plat\nform with Tresca at the time. The\nofficial change of front, however,\nmakes this unnecessary. The Italians\nare not the only ones who suffered\nthrough official suppression, similar\ntreatment having been accorded earl\nier to the Polish elements and to joint\nmeetings of several racial groups, in\ncluding English-speaking citizens.\nOn one occasoin, the Italian work\nwere obliged to hold a meeting on\nlot the outskirts of the\na\nr!\ncity, because the authorities prohib\nited one scheduled to take place in the\nAlhambra Theatre.\nIn Brockton the third attempt in\ntwo months by the Brockton Public\nForum to hold a mass gathering on\nthe O'Donnell Playgrounds proved\nsuccessful, and several thousand\nBrockton residents listened to Jerome\nT. DeHunt, chairman of the American\nLabor Party, speak on constitutional\nrights and the need for a Labor Par\nty. On Sunday, Oct. 7th DeHunt\nstood on a piazza facing these public\nplaygrounds and addressed his audi\nence, who were assembled on those\ngrounds.\nThe success in this instance is the\nmore notable as it was made in the\nface of an ordinance rushed through\nthe Brockton City Council forbidding\nthe holding of meetings on the O'Don\nnell playgrounds without a special\nwritten permit. No attempt was made\nto squelch the DeHunt meeting, not\nwithstanding that it was an open de\nfy of the Brockton officials w r ho have\nbeen interfering with labor gatherings\n\"This victory\", th^ Civil Liberties\n\"is most signifi\nThose who have followed the\nUnion declares,\nshoe strike in Brockton know how the\npolice have encroached on the civil\nrights of the workers. It is to be\nhoped that civil liberty will be re-es\ntablished there.\nCONVICT FORMER\nOFFICER OF LAW\nEx-Sheriff of Richland County and\nForme.r Toole County\nFound Guilty Of Larceny.\nResident\nSidney, Oct. 23.\u2014 Fred Sullivan,\nformerly of Toole County and more\nsheriff of Richland County,\nwas convicted in the district court\nhere on Saturday of grand larceny\nand was sentenced to the state prison\nfor a term of not less than one year\nnor more than two years,\nhere Monday in custody of Sheriff\nO'Brien for Deer Lodge to begin the\nservice of his term.\nSullivan was charged with the theft\nof a bunch of cattle belonging to the\nRed Water Land and Cattle company,\nof which M. S. Gunn of Helena, is the\nprincipal owner. The stolen cattle\nwere recovered from a pasture owned\nor controlled by Sullivan.\nHe left\nf f\nr \u00abs\ni\n1\n;-v\nVeal Is Nourishing\nOne of the best Meats you can serve your fam\nily is Veal.\nserved in a variety of ways, and the bones be\ning small, you get nearly solid meat for your\nmoney.\nOur supply is always ample to meet your needs\nIt is very nourishing, may be\nWE ALSO CARRY A FULL LINE OF\nGROCERIES\nHEIN'S MARKET\nG.N IS FULLY PRE\nPARED FOR RECORD\nFREIGHT MOVEMENT\nThousands of New Cars, 100 New Lo\ncomotives and Enlargement of Ter\nminal Facilities for Adequate Hand\nling of Harvest Time Flow of Ship\nments.\nSt. Paul, October 29.\u2014Preparations\nfor handling a record-breaking vol\nume of freight traffic this fall have\nbeen completed by the Great Northern\nRailway, the exceptional expansion of\nfaicilities assuring adequate service,\nfluring the busiest season of the year,\nto the large section of the Northwest\nserved by the Hill lines, it was dis\nclosed in a statement by executives\nhere. Additions and betterments to\nroad, terminals, motive power and\nequipment, which have so greatly in\ncreased the freight handiing capacity\nand operation efficiency of the trans\ncontinental system, resulted from the\ncompletion of a $30,000,000 improve\nment program this year, it was em\nphasized.\nThe program included new double\ntrack, automatic block signals, new\nand larger terminal yards, laying of\nnew freight and passenger locomotives\nand new cars. This year, the Great\nNorthern is prepared to handle a larg\ner traffic than ever before, officials\nsaid, car and locomotive supplies be\ning larger and this equipment being\nin exceptionally good condition, in\nfact in better condition than at any\ntime since the beginning of Federal\ncontrol in 1917.\nAmong the many improvements\nmade through maintenance of way\nwork are the laying of 2,250,000 cross\nties, the replacement of 45,000 tons of\nlighter-rail and the placing of 400,000\ncubic yards of ballasting. Mainte\nnance of equipment included the re\nbuilding of 3,600 freight cars, the re\nbuilding of twenty-five locomotives\nand rebuilding into all-steel cars of\nthirty diners and ten passenger and\nbaggage cars.\nExpenditure of large sums was re\nquired for the elimination of grade\ncrossings, new bridges and threstles,\ntelegraph and telephone facilities, au\ntomatic block signals, additional main\nand yard tracks, freight and passen\nger stations, fuel and water stations\nengine terminals, and coal and ore\ndocks. Freight equipment purchased\nincluded 2,000 box, 1,500 ore and 500\nautomobile cars. In addition to freight\ncars rebuilt,, extensive repairs were\nmade to several thousand other cars.\nThis $30,000,000 program was car\nried out in the face of poor earnings,\nsuch expenditure being justified only\nby the needs of patrons in Great\nNorthern territory and by confidence\nin the utlimate return of prosperity to\nthe fertile fields of the Northwest,\nofficials pointed out.\n\"The Great Northern is prepared\nadequately for an exceptionally busy\nsaid Chairman Louis W. Hill\nThe terri\nseason,\nof the board of directors,\ntory served by the Great Northeim\nRailway harvests its crops and ships\nmarket its heaviest load in the fall\nand this peak burden has been in mind\nprepartions to handle it efficiently\nhave been made.\"\nThis year the Great Northern is\nprepared to handle a larger traffic\nthan ever before. It has purchased\nnearly one hundred large, new loco\nmotives of the most modern type, as\nwell as 4,000 new freight cars. It\nhas built new track and improved old;\nit is equipped to do the people's work\nwell. A supply of cars is one of the\nimportant factors in such preparation.\nThe Great Northern not only owns\n1 ample equipment for the crop moving\nas\nPrie\u00ab\u00bb of all (404)\nCommoaitiM\nPrice\u00ab of V-Or'\nI Qoodyeof Tir\u00bb\n1919 1920 1921 19221824\n19141919191 19171\nL OOK at the way\nI Goodyear Tire\nprices have been\nkept consistently\nlower than the aver\nage for all commod\nities. Then think of\nthe improvements\nrepresented by that\nfinest of all Good\nyears, the new\n.\u00bbGoodyear Cord. De\nspite this, prices are\n37% lower now than\nin 1920, and 30%\nlower than in 1914.\nThis is the time to\nbuy Goodyears.\nAm Goodyear Service Station\nDealere toe mell and recom\nmend the new Goodyear\nCorde with the beveled All\nWeather Tread and back\nthem up with etandard\nGoodyear Service\nO. M. DONALDSON\nJOE REDMOND\nPlentywod, Montana.\nOOOh^lteAR\nseason, but it has these cars on its\nown lines ready for business and in\nexcellent condition.\"\n\"Actual records of equipment owned\nand on line show:\nOwned by On Great\nGreat Northern\nNorthern Lines\nBox Cars (including\nautomobile and\nfurniture cars)\nStock Cars\nRefrigerator Cars\n34,046\n1,946\n9,352\n20,315\n32,572\n1,893\n5,508\nOther Freight Cars....18,926\n58,899 65,659\nTotal Freight Cars\n\"So prepared the Great Northern\nis confident that it can give adequate\nservice to the Northwest throughout\nthe busiest season of the year. It ap\npreciates the patronage given and\nasks, in the interests of shippers as\nmuch as its interest, that shippers and\nreceivers of freight load cars to ca\npacity, load and unload promptly and\navoid diversion of shipments wherever\npossible, that the capacity of the sys\ntem be utilized fully and greatest ef\nficiency of service thus be assured.\"\nMrs. Schwantes Meets\nWith Accident At Bismarck\nMr. and Mrs. H. C. Schwantes, who\nleft here a few weeks ago are now\nlocated at Bismarck, N. D. Shortly\nafter their arrival in that city Mrs.\nSchwantes slipped on the wet pave\nment and broke two bones in her leg\nand is now laid up at the hospital.\nIt will be a considerable length of time\nbefore she will be able to be around\nagain.\u2014 Froid Tribune.\nPatronize the advertisers in this\npaper\u2014Patronize those who patronize\nyou.\nA Hurry-tip Call\nA VERY IMPORTANT business problem\ncame up in a large southern bank and it called\nfor quick a ction. An officer of the bank must\nhurry to another city 100 miles away to attend\nto this business that very day.\nBut he missed his train.\nIt seemed that this important business must fail\nBut a flying machine was near by and that\nbanker jumped into the machine and quickly\narrived at the place where duty called him.\nThis is an unusual case but it shows the deter\nmination of the banker to do all that can be\ndone to handle every problem successfully.\nYou will always find this bank ready\nto do all that we can do to solve the\nproblems that are presented to us.\nThink it over.\nTHE\nFirst National Bank\nMember Federal Reserve System\n\nr\nPLENTYWOOD, MONT.\nRE-ELECT ELY\ni LABOR CHIEF\nFOR MONTANA\nSAND COULEE MAN DEFEATS\nGILDEA BY HUGE MAJORITY\n30 PUT. OF MEMBERS VOTE.\nj __\nHelena, Oct. 26.\u2014Stephen Ely of\nSand Coulee will serve his third con\nsecutive term as president of the Mon\ntana Federation of Labor, as the re\nsult of a vote recently taken and\nwhich has just been tabulated by a\ncanvassing board in Helena, and made\npublic Friday by E. H. Man son, sec\nretary treasurer. Ely received 2,34.)\n\u25a0votes as compared to 757 for Charles\nGildea of Butte.\nIt is said the combined vote was less\nthan 30 per cent of the membership of\nthe state federation.\nOther officers elected are James An\nderson, vice president; E. H. Manson,\nsecretary-treasurer, and the following\nmembers of the executive board: Dis\nrict Nto. 2, William Simpson of Hel\nena; District No. 3, E. F. Keltt of Mis\nsoula; District No. 4, Pete D. Tiddell\nof Anaconda; District No. 5, William\nWinterrowd of Great Falls; United\nMine Workers of America, member-at\nlarge, Ed Davis of Roundup; Mine,\nMill and Smelter Workers, Patrick\nBeloughry, of Butte.\nThe canvassing board, whir# has\nbeen in session here for several days,\nwas composed of Peter Hallberg of\nHelena Trades and Labor assembly;\nJames T. Graham of Livingston, rep\nresenting the Federal Labor union of\nthat city; James E. Winsby of Great\nFalls, representing the Cascade Coun\nty Trades and Labor assembly; Cecil\nSederholm of Sand Coulee, represent\ning District 27, United Mine Workers\nof America, and T. P. Wilburn of Mis\nsoula, representing the Painters' un\nion of the Garden city.\nFORD CAR NUMBER\n8, 50\u00ab, 000 FINISHED\nDetroit, Mich., Oct. 29.\u2014Ford Motor\nNo. 8,500,000 went off the assembly\nline at the Ford Motor Company's\nplant in Highland Park on October 4th\nit is announced. The last half million\nmotors were produced in seven days\nless than three months, for Motor No.\n8.000,000 went out July 11, this year.\nOne factory of the Ford Motor Com\npany, located at Northville, Mich.,\nnear Detroit, is devoted exclusively to\nthe manufacture of valves for Ford\nModel T motors and for Fordson\nTractor motors. The plant emplays\n350 men working in three eight-hour\nshifts and turns out 85,000 Ford mo\ntor valves and 10,000 Fordson valves\ndaily. Since it was opened in March,\n1920, the Northville plant has pro\nduced more than 44,000,000 valves.\nDemand for ammonium sulphate for\nfertilizer is growing -rapidly. During\nfive months nearly 7,000 tons of it\nshipped from the River Rouge\np ant of the Ford Motor Company to\nall parts of the United States. It is\na by-product of coke, carries from 20\nto 21 per cent available nitrogen and\nis known as one of the world's best\ncommercial carriers of that element.\nwere\nWe carry no sample copies as ad*\nvertising bait\u2014Place your ad before\nreaders who want a paper by paying\nfor it.\nAdvertise where it pays\u2014circula\ntion 2,000 every week.\nFROID DELEGATES\nENJOY MEETING\nAT BUTTE\nMrs. O. B. McCabe has returned\nfrom Butte where she attended the\nMontana Rebekah Assembly. She re\nports a very pleasant trip and an en\ntertaining and instructive lodge ses\nsion\n___\nI __ D\nGlasgow Folk Hear DOIT1DS\ni pj ery Cross\nij*ii\nGlow l/D I tie lilllS\nj\nThe following Assembly officers\nwere elected for the ensuing yer:\nPresident\u2014Ethel C. Hirsch.\nVice. Pres.\u2014Bell Kempter.\nWarden\u2014Jennie Bywaters.\nSecretary\u2014Nellie W. Neill.\nTreas.\u2014May Bonnie.\n1. O. O. F. GRAND LODGE\nC. C. Scott, who attended as a dele\ngate to the I. O. O. F. Grand Lodge,\nis expected back Saturday of this\nweek, having spent a few days over\nin Idaho with one of his daughters,\nMrs. Regnoll C. Scott of Cour de\nThe I. O. O. F. Grand Lodge officers\nE. C. Collins, grand\nplppfprl wprp*\nmaster, Billings; E. O. Kinchey, Lew_\nistown, deputy grand master; G. J.\nBonine, of Havre, grand warden; R.\nW. Kemp, Missoula, grand treasurer;\nE. H. Goodman, Townsend, grand rep\nresentative, two year term; Sam P.\nJohnson, Butte, grand representative,\none year term.\nthe hills north of town direct\nions on\nGlasgow, Oct. 19.\u2014Several expos\ned the attention of Glasgow folk a few\nnights ago to a flaming fiery cross on\nelevation overlooking the city. It\nan\nresh\nFROM THE FACTOR?\n19\ncl\nTOBA\nROLL YOUR\nOWN WTIH\nRIZ1A CIOOC\nBPESSATOQBi\nfi\n50,000 Bushels\nOATS\nMUST BE FREE\nFROM WILD OATS\nPrice: 30 cents\nFarmers Club Elevator\nic nnt known who sponsored the\nhnt it is believed to have been a\nb e oinf Ihe local Klu Klux Klan.\nS, Th\u00e8 Waft 1 made its presence known\nin GlLeow about 18 omnths ago when\nthree masked and robed men made a\nto the Deaconess hospital.\nem\nCALUMET\nThe Economy BAKING P OWOCft\nI Is truly the\nworld's great* 1/\nest baking\n\n<9\n\u2022<2\nIt has\nproduces\nPure\nFoods 1\nBetter\nBakings\nK\u00d6AK >nq\nCA1DMB\nV \u00ab'\"\u00ab\u2022mi* l\nSales\nIntimes\nas much\nas that\nof any\nother\nbrandw\ntor over\none third\noS a cen*\nfury\nESST BT TEST\nA\nIt\nQT\u00b0 P\noto\nn\nAT\nKAVON'S GARAGE\nAnd get that grade of oil for your tractor or car, at prices\nthat you will buy. Remember we have a battery for ev\nery car\u2014a part for every battery. Agency for Overland\nand Star Automobiles, Fisk and Federal Tires.\nSAMSON and RUMELY TRACTORS\nR\u00bb\nSince then speculation has\nas to whether the local kl an\ntion was still in existence \u00b0u\nlieved the recent demon*\u2122\nan answer to rumors that Vk\nhere was defunct. klar,\nWn ri\nhte","height":"27309","width":"20898"}}
